    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-02-10T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-02-10T19:00:00-05:00" n="500"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d500">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/2–1152:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 500<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France (<persName corresp="#p_BRUCEDKE1"
                            type="from">Bruce</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-02-11T01:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 11 [<hi rend="italic">12</hi>], 1952—1 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4925. Attention <persName corresp="#p_GORDONL1">Lincoln Gordon</persName>. Ref
                        <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 4924, Feb 11.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d500fn1">
                        <ref target="#d499">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>French Defense Minister presented breakdown of 1400 billion budget
                            divided as follows (all numbers in billion francs):</p>
                        <p>Army 340, Air Force 220, Navy 125, common services 125, Defense Dept
                            civil expenditures 137, third slice infrastructure 15, and Indochina and
                                <gloss target="#t_DOT1">DOT</gloss>’s 438 broken down into 380 for
                            Army, 33 for Air Force, and 25 for Navy. Defense Ministry and <gloss
                                target="#t_MAAG1">MAAG</gloss> both estimate that expenditures of
                            1400, allocated according to foregoing breakdown, would support an army
                            of 14 ⅓ divisions, but in lower state of readiness than set by <gloss
                                target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>’s particularly in divisional backup.
                            Eighteen months’ conscription period could be maintained with somewhat
                            slower call up. Air Force estimated as having 27 squadrons of 478 planes
                            with better planes and effectiveness considerably greater than the 26
                            squadrons in being latter part of 1951 as against 33 squadrons
                            recommended by <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>’s. Navy would be same
                            as 1951 plus two destroyer escorts and six coastal minesweepers due
                            under <gloss target="#t_MDAP1">MDAP</gloss>.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>1400 estimate contains continuation of old procurement contracts of
                        approximately 38 for Army, 68 for Air and 45 for Navy. Provides new
                        procurement and production contracts amounting to only 60 for Army, 19 for
                        Air and nothing for Navy. French official states implication of small amount
                        in new contracts for Air is that jet aircraft needed in 1953 would have to
                        come from <gloss target="#t_OSP1">OSP</gloss> or end-item aid. The 1400
                        estimate provides little production for buildup in 1953.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The 1400 budget shld give a force politically viable in relation German
                        contribution. The buildup of French and German air forces could be kept in
                        balance within <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BRUCEDKE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bruce</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
